Melbourne House Price Regression Models

Executive Summary:

An investment into real estate, often in the form of a primary residence, is the largest financial investment many of us will make in our lifetime. A sound understanding of how to approach valuing a residential property could save prospective homeowners tens if not hundreds of thousands of dollars on an overvalued property, or result in similair profits on an undervalued property.

In this report data from houses in Melbourne - including size, location, car spaces and price - are analysed with the aim of developing and refining a regression model that can be applied to value residential properties.

To make the data more manageable we only consider the suburbs of Brunswick, Craigieburn and Hawthorn.

1.3: Finding Association 1

Model 1: A simple Linear regression between two variables: Price and Plot Size

lmBA <- lm(Price ~ BuildingArea, data = MelbHousingSubset)

Visualised:

plot1 <- ggplot(MelbHousingSubset, aes(x = BuildingArea, y = Price)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + labs(x = "Building Area", y = "Price (AUD)", title = "                                         Price v Building Area")

The model produces a p-value less than 0.01 (2.2e-16), therefore we can conclude with 99% confidence that there is a correlation between Price and Building Area for these properties.

However, the model also produces an R-Squared Value of 0.1725. This is a poor fit and implies that Building Area only accounts for 17.25% of the variation in the observed house prices.

From observation of the plot, there are outliers that may be corrupting the model.

Consider properties with area less than 5 square metres and more than 300 square metres as outliers.

1.4: Finding Association 2

House prices are complex and are likely to be influenced by many factors.

Extending the model to include Suburb as a second explanatory variable may increase its predictive power.

Model 3: Multiple linear regression model between Price, and Building Area and Suburb.

lmBA3 <- lm(Price ~ BuildingArea + Suburb, data = MelbHousingSubset)
summary(lmBA3)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Price ~ BuildingArea + Suburb, data = MelbHousingSubset)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -4074050  -248461   -26674   166018  5479862 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                    Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)        509756.7    62451.0   8.163 3.99e-15 ***
## BuildingArea         4435.4      346.9  12.786  < 2e-16 ***
## SuburbCraigieburn -660277.3    72911.5  -9.056  < 2e-16 ***
## SuburbHawthorn     400715.9    72543.5   5.524 5.87e-08 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 609900 on 414 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.425,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.4208 
## F-statistic:   102 on 3 and 414 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

As with earlier models, Model 3 produces a p-value less than 0.01 (2.2e-16), therefore we can conclude with 99% confidence that there is a correlation between Price and Building Area and Suburb for these properties.

Adding the second explanatory variable, Suburb, improves the fit of the model, increasing its explanatory power from 17.05% to 42.08%.

As Suburb is a categorical variable the interpretation of the coefficient is different than that of a numerical variable. The coefficients are binary - as opposed to scalar - inputs to the house price.

The model should be interpreted as saying that a property in Brunswick has an intercept (i.e when building area is 0) of $509,756.7, a property in Cragieburn has an intercept of -$150,520.6, and a property in Hawthorn has an intercept of $910,472.6.

Formally, the fitted lines for the three suburbs under Model 3 are:

Brunswick: Price = 509,756.7 + (4,435.4 x Building Area)

Cragieburn: Price = -150,520.6 + (4,435.4 x Building Area)

Hawthorn: Price = 910,472.6 + (4,435.4 x Building Area)

Visualised:

plot4 <- ggPredict(lmBA3) + labs(
     x = "Building Area (Square Metres)", 
     y = "Price (AUD)", 
     title = "                                  Price v Area"
    )
plot4 + scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar)

This visualisation shows that house prices in Hawthorn are higher (all else equal) than those in Brunswick, which are higher than those in Craigieburn.

Adding a further variable - Car Spaces - to the model may further increase its predictive power.

Model 4: Multiple linear regression model between Price, and Building Area, Suburb and Car Spaces.

lmBA4 <- lm(Price ~ BuildingArea + Suburb + Car, data = MelbHousingSubset)
summary(lmBA4)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Price ~ BuildingArea + Suburb + Car, data = MelbHousingSubset)

## Multiple R-squared:  0.477,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.4718 
## F-statistic: 91.66 on 4 and 402 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Once again the Model has a statistically significant p-value at 0.1% confidence level.

Adding the third explanatory variable, Car Spaces, has increased the explanatory power of the model from 42.08% to 47.18%

The Suburb coefficients have changed with the new Model. Under Model 4 a property in Brunswick has an intercept (i.e when building area is 0 and the number of Car spaces is 0) of $333,560.7, a property in Cragieburn has an intercept of -$450,547, and a property in Hawthorn has an intercept of $696,997.5

Formally, the fitted lines for the three suburbs under Model 4 are:

Brunswick: Price = 333,560.7 + (3,761.7 x Building Area) + (220,740.5 x Car Spaces)

Cragieburn: Price = -447,547.0 + (3,761.7 x Building Area) + (220,740.5 x Car Spaces)

Hawthorn: Price = 696,997.5 + (3,761.7 x Building Area) + (220,740.5 x Car Spaces)

plot5 <- ggPredict(lmBA4)+ labs(
     x = "Building Area (Square Metres)", 
     y = "Price (AUD)", 
     title = "                                  Price v Area"
    )
plot5 + scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar)

This visualisation confirms that house prices have a positive correlation with Car Spaces, with more car spaces resulting in a steeper fitted line (all else equal).

Analysis of Residuals is as follows:

plot(lmBA4)

From observation of the Residuals v Fitted, Normal Q-Q, Scale-Location and Residuals v Leverage plots there are outliers and highly leveraged data points that may be confounding the Model.

The Residuals v Fitted Plot identifies data points 2297, 34330 and 15697 as potential outliers.

The Normal Q-Q plot has highly skewed tails, indicating non-normality in the data, and identifies 2297, 34330 and 15697 as outliers.

The Scale-Location plot identifies 2297, 34330, and 15697 as outliers

The Residuals vs Leverage Plot identifies data point 2297 with a Cook’s distance greater than 1 and 15697 and 21254 with Cook’s distance greater than 0.5

Data points 2297, 15697, and 34330 are consistently identified as outliers and their removal may improve the Model’s predictive power.

1.5: Impact of Outliers

Removing outliers (properties with Building area of more than 300 square metres, or less than 5 square metres and price higher than $6 million).

outliers2 <- which(MelbHousingSubset$BuildingArea > 300 | MelbHousingSubset$BuildingArea < 5 | MelbHousingSubset$Price > 6000000)
MelbHousingSubset.Clean2 <- MelbHousingSubset[-outliers2,]

1.6: Prediction

We can use our final model to predict the house price of a property in Hawthorn, with two car spaces and 100sqm building area.

NewHouse <- data.frame(BuildingArea = c(100),
                             Suburb = c("Hawthorn"),
                                Car = c(2))
Pred <- predict(lmBA5, NewHouse, interval = "confidence")
Pred
##       fit     lwr     upr
## 1 1255747 1165271 1346224

According to our model, we can say with 95% confidence that the value of our Hawthorn property, with 100sqm of Building Area and two car spaces, is between $1,165,271 and $1,346,224 with a mean expected value of $1,255,747.
